DIV2.P:
Verse 425. Here is a most just and beautiful Comparison. The Situation of the Fishes, so poetically rendered by Mr. Pope, must touch every compassionate Mind;

All naked of their Element, and bare,

The Fishes pant, and gasp in thinner Air.

Vida, as you may observe, is the most regular of all these Essayists. His first Book is on

Invention, or the Provision of Matter;
the next is

We have a Proverb in Scotland,
Cocks are free of Horse-Corn;
meaning to imply that People are liberal or profuse of what belongs to another.

Again, we have,
Use a Cat to the Churn, and she will call i Custom;


signifying, if you accustom your Servants, or other Folks, to make frequent Use of what is yours, they will think, at last, that they have acquired a Right to it.

Statius, describing a general Silence and Quiet, says,



The weary Mountains nodded their Heads;

And the Seas rested or slept, leaning against the Shore.
